PSpecteR Description

Briely, PSpecteR is a proteomic data visualization application which generates mass spectra and other graphics from mass spec files (mzML, mzXML, ThermoFisher raw), spectra-associated protein ID files (mzid), and fasta database files (fa, fasta).

Abstract

The preferred method to identify and quantify expressed proteins within biological systems is liquid chromatography coupled to mass spectrometry (LC-MS), where either intact or digested proteins are eluted from an LC column, ionized, and analyzed with MS. The resulting LC-MS data files are compressed in binary formats (.raw) and thus require specialized analysis software which complicates data visualization and quality control processes. Using existing packages in R, we developed PSpecteR: a graphical user interface (GUI) to interact with proteomic LC-MS ThermoFisher .raw files. PSpecteR allows users to import .raw or XML-formatted MS data and either call a protein identification algorithm to match the spectra to amino acid sequences from a fasta database (e.g., MSPathFinder or MSGF+) or provide the identification results (i.e., .mzid). Using peptide-spectrum matches, raw MS/MS spectra are automatically annotated with multiple in-silico fragment ions of peptides that the user can interactively chose and change. PSpecteR also offers multiple interactive visualizations of MS data and the exportation of all figures, tables, and spectra. PSpecteR is a user- and coder-friendly GUI which demonstrates that, like code, GUIs can be flexible and open source.

App Installation

Install App on Windows

  1. Go to the google drive and copy the “PSpecteR” folder to your desktop. Link to the PSpecteR Google Drive.

  2. On your desktop, click PSpecteR’s “LaunchApp” folder followed by the “R_Version” folder. Download R 3.6.1 by clicking “R-3.6.1-win.exe.” This should take about 20 seconds.

  3. After completing the previous step, this is the only step you need to complete whenever launching the app again. Return to the “Launch App” folder and click “LAUNCH_windows.bat.” All the dependencies should install for you, and the app will automatically open in your web browser. For your own reference, a table will print during an succesful upload.

Install App on macOS

  1. Go to the google drive and copy the “PSpecteR” folder to your desktop. Link to the PSpecteR Google Drive.

  2. On your desktop, click PSpecteR’s “LaunchApp” folder followed by the “R_Version” folder. Download R 3.6.1 by clicking “R-3.6.1.pkg.” This should take about 20 seconds.

  3. After completing the previous step, this is the only step you need to complete whenever launching the app again. Return to the “Launch App” folder and click “LAUNCH_macOS.command.” All the dependencies should install for you, and the app will automatically open in your web browser. For your own reference, a table will print during an succesful upload.

Reasons why the app might not have opened the first time

  1. The “LAUNCH” files check that the right version of R is installed. A warning will let you know if the wrong version is being used.

  2. If you have Bioconductor, the shell or command.exe version of R will need to be updated. This can be googled and completed in the command line.

  3. If it isn’t these two errors, please let me know at david.degnan@pnnl.gov. Thanks!

1. Upload Files Page

Page Description

This page allows you to upload mass spec (MS) files, protein ID (ID) files, and protein database files (FA). You can choose to use pre-loaded test files at the bottom of the page. One tests the entire app and the other only tests the MSGF+ peptide database search algorithm.

How to Use

  1. Click the “1. Upload” option in the navigation bar at the top of the page.
  2. Click the “Required MS File” text to open the collapsible side bar.
  3. Click the “.mzML, .mzXML, .raw” button to open your directory. Click on any of the aforementioned file types and then click “open.”
  4. A successful load will be indicated with a print out of the file path on the right.
  5. Select activation method with a drop down-box.
  6. The MS file can be visualized with Scan & Seq. Users may add ID data. Note than an unsupported file type is given with a warning.
  7. Pre-loaded test files are available. If you would like to test the app with an already generated .mzid file, click the first test file slider and proceed to 2. Scan & Seq.
  8. If you would like to test peptide database search tool MSGF+, click the second slider to load a small .mzML file and a FA database file.

2. Scan & Seq Page

Page Description

Scan & Seq allows you to see how well a peptide sequence maps to a specific MS2 (or MS1) scan. Visualize fragmentation patterns, post-translational modifications, extracted ion chromatograms, the best identified fragment ion per peptide, and more.

Set Filters

  1. Click the 1. Filtering Settings box and ensure the right Ion Types have been selected. Notice that they are pre-selected based on the previously chosen Activation Method in the Upload Page.
  2. Spectrum Ranges: You may zoom in on the image by using the sliders or by typing in a value or range for either the intensity or m/z. Click the update buttons after typing in a value. You must input these values when taking an image snapshot to save the image for later. Otherwise, the entire image will export and not one with a zoomed in range.
  3. Spectrum Settings: Set the fragment tolerance (how far off theoeretical fragments can be from experimental fragments in PPM). Then set the minimum intensity value that will be plotted. The minimum isotopic percentage is the smallest isotopic peak size that will be visualized based on percentage of size as compared to the highest peak. Set this value, and then choose whether you would like the traditional spectra view or not. When viewing MS1 scans, it is highly recommended that you disable this feature. Also, choose whether you would like to annotate the spectra with its fragment name (not fully functional yet).
  4. XIC Ranges: Set the XIC ranges, similar to 2.2 Spectrum Ranges.
  5. XIC Settings: An XIC (extracted ion chromatogram) graphs the intensity vs retention time peaks across all MS1 scans with the XIC MZ value. The XIC MZ Value here is autofilled with the MSn scan’s Precursor MZ (Pre.MZ) value. The XIC Charge value plots the traces for m+n peaks that are XIC MZ value + n * 1/XIC Charge. The Precursor Tolerance is how large the search window is to identify the peak across MS1 scans.
  6. Sequence Settings: Select the background color for the “All Ions” graphic. Next, input a sequence if you would like to try one. B, J, O, U, X, and Z are not accetable amino acids, and the sequence must have at least two letters. It cannot contain spaces or extra characters.
  7. Scan (Table) Settings: Choose which columns of the Scan Table you would like to see. Column options can be searched, all selected, or all deselected.

  8. Take Image Snapshot: Take high-res snapshots of the rendered plots. Remember to zoom in with the ranges options, if applicable. These images can be exported. See “Exportations” to learn how.
  9. Export Data: Click one of these buttons to convert the XML data to a CSV. See “Exportations” to learn how.

View Graphics

  1. Spectrum: Hover over the image and zoom by dragging a box over where you would like to zoom in. Click the Autoscale button to return to the original view. All graphics in PSpecteR can be zoomed and only have certain datapoints selected. Hover over the peaks to get the identified ion name, m/z value, and intensity value. Settings 1-3 in the sidebar control the inputs to generate this graphic. Specific fragments can be selected with the table under “Tab.”
  2. Heatmap: See the ppm error (how far off the theoretical value is from the experimental value) per amino acid per ion type. PPM error is calculated by (exp - theo / theo * 1e6).
  3. XIC: An XIC (extracted ion chromatogram) graphs the intensity vs retention time peaks across all MS1 scans for peaks with the XIC MZ value.
  4. All Ions: See all identified ion types per amino acid. Hover-over to see ion type, and m/z and intensity values.
  5. Tab: This table allows the user to see all identified fragments. Click table rows to have the data isolated by ion type (not fully functional). Tables can be sorted by clicking the down and up arrows by the column titles.
  6. Bar: See a barchart of all identified ion types.
  7. Scan: Click a row to visualize the data assoicated with a specific scan. Add/remove columns to the table with “Scan (Table) Settings.” Tables can be searched (dialog boxes) and sorted (arrows). To select a range, like from 3 to 5, type 3 ... 5 into the search box.
  8. Sequence: View the best fit (lowest ppm error) a,b,c or x,y,z ion per amino acid. Hover-over to see the PPM error of each fragment.

3. Visualize Post-Translational Modifications Page

PAGE NOT COMPLETE

Page Description

Visualize PTM allows you to determine if a specific Scan & Seq pairing would be a better fit based on one or more post-translational modifications. Many PTM combinations can be searched here and automatically ranked by the best fit. Desired outputs can be added back to the 3. Scan & Seq page and exported.

Set Filters

  1. Select Spectra: Scan & sequence information will be pulled from the last clicked entry in 3. Scan & Seq. These can be chaged by user input.
  2. Choose Modifications: Select all desired modifications (up to 15) that you would like to be tested. This selection box is exactly like 2.7 Scan (Table) Settings without a select all option. The most common PTMs are listed at the top and can be easily selected with the “Common PTMs” button. Use clear to remove all selected PTMs. Extra PTMs can be added in “C. Unimod Glossary” under the More tab. You can also set the max number of modifications per sequence and max number of modifications per peptide (not functional). We encourage you to test out what you can of this page.
  3. The rest of this page is coming soon!

4. Protein Tree Page

Page Description

This page allows you to visualize how every identified peptide sequence maps to its database protein.

Set Filters

  1. Protein Tree Range: Set the range values of the Match graphic. See “2.2 Spectrum Ranges.”
  2. Protein Tree Settings: Set the Q-value tolerance (minimum Q-value). Q-value is an adjusted p-value and is a measurement of the pairing between a scan and sequence. Use the slider to remove contaminants, as some sequences match strongly to known contaminants instead of a protein from the database.
  3. Take Image Snapshot: Take a high-res snapshot of the images. See “Exportations” for more details.
  4. Export Data: Export the data in the Protein Tree table (only table on the page). See “Exportations” for more details.

View Graphics

  1. Match: Click a protein on the table to see how every identified peptide sequence maps to that protein. Hover-over information reveals the scan number and sequence.
  2. Bar: See the number of times each amino acid in the literature sequence was identified.
  3. Literature Sequence: View the full literature sequence with regions identified by peptides in green.

DB Search: MSGF+

Page Description

Interface with the MSGF+ algorithm. It is highly recommended to practice with the “Test MSGF” option on the Upload page. MSGF+ version 2019.07.13 is used with this app, and it requires the generation of a configuration (config) text file. The majority of this page is used to generate the config file. All outputs from MSGF+ are saved to a timestamped folder in the Downloads folder. MSGF+ only accepts mzML and mzXML files. Results are automatically loaded into PSpecteR.

Generate Configuration File

  1. Precursor Tolerance: Set symmetric tolerance values. For example 15ppm will be set 0.000015 Da to the left and the right.
  2. Modifications: Set the max number of modifications per peptide. If this value is large, the search will be slow. Then set modifications that are static (applied to every possible peptide) and/or dynamic (applied to multiple combinations of peptides).
  3. MS Acquisition: Select the fragmentation method, instrument, enzyme, and number of tolerable termini (which indicates how tryptic an enzyme was in a bottom-up technique). Remember that bottom-up involves the use of an enzyme to break a peptide before mass spec acquisition. Next, set the isotopic error range in PPM, which takes into account the error introduced by choosing a non-monoisotopic peak for fragmentation. It’s useful for accurate precursor ion masses.
  4. Other MSGF Settings: Set whether the target decoy database will be searched (improves algorithm results), the number of threads, the min/max peptide length, the min/max charge, the number of permissable matches per spectrum, the minimum number of acceptable peaks per spectrum, and whether to output additional features.
  5. Additional .mzML Files: Additional mzML files can be added or removed. Only the first mzML & mzid file will be visualized in the app.
  6. Run MSGF+: Click the “Run MSGF+” button to start the peptide database search tool. A green checkmark will let you know the algorithm is running, and the resulting data will be written in the “Output” tab (Apple products) or in the command.exe window (Microsoft products). The algorithm can be cancelled at anytime. The outputted .mzid file is loaded into PSpecteR, and exported to its own folder in downloads along with the configuration text file.

MSGF+ Inputs/Outputs

  1. Input: The input page will let you know everything that will be written in the text file as well as the names of all inputted files. Watch it update in real time as you adjust algorithmic parameters!
  2. Output: Shows the output of the algorithm as it runs. Here is an example of a complete run:

A Feature Plot

Page Description

Visualize the metadata from the “Scan” table in “2. Scan & Seq.”

Functions & Graphs

  1. Subset Data: Since the MS data can be quite large, choose a random subset size if desired. 6 means that 1/6 of the data will be randomly selected and visualized.
  2. Select Variables: Select the Feature Plot’s X, Y, and label variables. More visualization options are enabled when an ID file is included.
  3. Take Image Snapshot: Take a high-res snapshot of the data. See “Exportations” for more info.
  4. Feature Plot: Visualize the metadata across all scans.

B MS1 Feature Plot

Page Description

A special feature plot which visualizes metadata from only MS1 scans.

Functions & Graphs

  1. MS2 Annotation: Annotate each point (which represent an MS1 scan) an associated MS2 scan if there is any.
  2. Set X Axis: Change the X-axis from Retention Time to Scan Number.
  3. Take Image Snapshot: Take a high-res snapshot of the MS1 Feature Plot. See “Exportations” for more details.
  4. MS1 Feature Plot: Visualize metadata from MS1 scans.

C Unimod Glossary

Page Description

View and append the database of post-translatinal modifications PSpecteR uses in its Vis PTM page.

Functions

  1. Select Columns: Select columns from the Unimod Glossary to view.
  2. Append Table: Add post-translation modifications with a pop-up window or upload as a CSV (CSV upload currently not functional).

  3. Unimod Glossary: The table can be searched and sorted.

Exportations

Exporting Data

Click any “Export Data” button.

  1. Use the sliders to the left of each row title to select which data is exported.

  2. Numerical data will include the ability to manually input ranges.

  3. Use “Select All” to enable all the sliders to turn on.

  4. All CSVs are automatically named for you, but feel free to change.

  5. Export the data or exit. It will appear in your downloads folder with the name given in step 4.

Exporting Images

Click the “Export Snapshot Images” button. It does not matter which page you are currently in.

  1. Select a table row to visualize the image.

  2. Delete all the images or delete that row’s image, if desired.

  3. Export data as a PNG…

  4. ..or a JPG.

  5. PDF export may not work (still testing).

  6. Exit if necessary.

All exported images are written to their own timestamped folder in the Downloads folder.
